{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_chapel_ver01/data/sn87055779/00517017656/1923122201/0304.xml":{"full_text":"i liBTTER FROM RICHARD SUM\nMBits TO BEATRICE\nGRIMSHAW\nMT DEAR BEATRICE:\nI didn't answer your letter Im\nmediately because I wanted to think\nV well about It before writing.\nIt was very strange; Indeed, a\nvery aggravating kind' ef a letter.\nI might say a very nagging kind of\na letter.\nI did not want to write you until\nI had gotten over being angry about\nIt.\nDo you know, Bee, I never until\n1 read that letter had detected a\nnagging spirit In you. In this re\nspect I thought you were different\nfrom other women. I thought you\nwould not Impute motives to me\nthat were furthest from my\nthoughts.\nI wonder why it la, my dear Bee,\nthat a short separation can change\n'the viewpoint of one or both those\nseparated as greatly as yours and\nmlna seem to have been changed.\nEvidently for you, absence has not\nmade the heart grow fonder.\nI remember thinking back there\nIn the east that you had such a\nplacidly sweet disposition. I felt\nthat I could always rest eecure In\nyour quiet regard, and now all at\nonce I find that you are something\nentirely different.. I find I do not\nknow you af all, Bee.\nIs It possible that you are jealous\nof Miss Perler? Why, my dear, that\npopular moving picture star would\nI not look at poor me.\nI The greatest and most powerful\nand famous men In the land might\nfe\u00abl groa.tly flattered It aha would\nturn her eyee their way. She la\nsomething quite different front the\naverage woman.\nSometimes I ha.ro come to think\nthat even with my abort acquain\ntance with her, I know her now even\nbetter than I know yon.\nBy the way, I wonder if you hare\never known a man by the name of\nSydney Carton? Hj\u00bb telle me he is\nthe most Intimate friend of John\nAlden Prescott, who married your\nfriend, Lee He Hamilton. He aim\nseems to have known Miss Perler\nvery well before she went into pic\ntures and for the last few days\nsince he has been here they have\nbeen constantly together.\nIt doesn't take very much to set\nthe gossips going in Hollywood and\nthe whole c61ony is agog over the\nidea that at last Paula Perler is al\nlowing some man to shower her\nwith his undivided attention.\nShe has kept entirely to herself\nexcept when, for business reason*\nshe has had to show herself at the\nhotel with Abe Einstein. On these\noccasions she has always insisted\nthat I go with them.\nCarton seems a pretty decent fel\nlow and the strange part of it is\nthat Miss Perier seems, as far as I\ncan see, more devoted to him than\nhe is to her. f\nThere Is some bond between them,\nhowever, greater than ordinary\nfriendship.\n(Copyright, 1923, NEA Service, Inc.)\nTOMORROW: Richard Summers\ncontinues the letter\u2014Materal in\nstinct in Paula.\n1\nSAX ROHMIK^n\nBEXJIN HERB TODAY\nPaul Harley, criminal investigator,\nIa engaged by Sir Charles Abingdon\nto Investigate the reason of the sur\n\u25bcelllanco of Sir Charles by persona\nunknown to him. While Harley ia\ndining at the Abingdon home Sir\nCharles falls from his chair in a dy\ning state. Dr. McMurdoch pro\nnounces death due to heart-failure.\nThe last words uttere\u2019d by Abing\ndon are \u201cNicol Brinn\" and \u201cFire\nTongue.\u201d Harley Insists that Sir\nCharles was poisoned and goes to\nask Nicol Brinn the meaning ol\n\u201cFire-Tongue.\u201d Brinn admits that\nhe learned Its meaning in India bul\nrefuses to divulge the secret. Paul\ninvestigates the life of Ormuz Khan,\nan Oriental, with whom Phil Ablng\ndon, daughter of Sir Charles,, is\nfriendly.\nNOW GO ON WITH THE STORY\n$3 \"Fii^lly, Benson,\" said Harleys\n\u201cwhat else did you bring into the\nroom after Sir Charles and I had\nentered?\u201d\n\u201cSoup, sir. Here is the tureen, on\nthe sideboard, and all the soup plates\nof the service in use that night. Ol\ncourse, sir, I can\u2019t say which were\nthe actual plates used.\u201d\nPaul Harley inspected the plates, a\nset of fine old Derby ware, and gazed\nmeditatively at the silver ladle. \u201cDid\nthe maid?* Jones, handle any ol\nthese?\u201d he asked.\n\u201cNo, sir\u201d\u2014emphatically. \u201cShe was\npreparing to bring the trout from\nthe kitchen.\u201d\n\u201cBut I saw her in the room.\u201d\n\u201cShe had brought in the fish\nplates, a\u2019sauce boat, and two toast\nracks, sir. She put them here, on\nthe sideboard. But they were never\nbrought to the tablg.\u201d\n\"H\u2019m. Has Jones left?\u201d\n\u201cYes, sir. She was under notice.\nBut after her rudeness, Mrs. Howett\npacked her oft right away. She left\nthe very next day after poor Sir\nCharles died.\u201d\n\u201cWhere has she gone?\u201d\n\"To a married sister, I believe,\nuntil she finds a new Job. Mrs. How\nett has the address.\"\nAt this moment Mrs. Howett en\ntered, bearing a tablecloth and a\nnumber of serviettes.\ni n is was ine ciom, ene earn,\nspreading It out< \"but which of the\nserviettes were used I cannot say.\u201d\n\u201cAllow me to look,\u201d replied Paul\nHarley.\nOne,by one he began to Inspect the\nserviettes, opening each In turn and\nexamining it critically.\n\u201cWhat have we here!\u201d he ex\nclaimed, presently. \u201cHave black\nberries been served within the week,\nMrs. Howett?\"\n\u201cWe never had them on the ta\nble. Mr. Harley. Sir Charles\u2014God\nrest him\u2014said they irritated the\nstbmach. Good gracious!\u201d She turned\nto Benson. \"How is it I never no\nticed those stains, and what can\nbAve caused them\nTho serviette which Paul Harley\nheld outstretched waa covered all\nover with dark purple spots.\nCHAPTER Xy\nTho Veil is Raised.\nRising from the writing table In\nthe library, Paul Harley crossed to\nthe mantelpiece and stared long and\nhungrily at a photograph In a silver\nframe. So closely did he concen\ntrate upon it that he induced a sort\nof auto-hypnosis, so that Phil Abing\ndon seemed to smile at him sadly.\n\u2666\u25a0Benson,\u201d he called, opening the\nlibrary door. As the man came along\ntho hall: \u201cI have written a note to\nMr. Innee, my secretary,\u201d he ex\nplained. \u2018There It Is, on the table.\nWhen the district messenger, for\nwhom you telephoned, arrives, give\nhim the parcel and the note. He Is\nto accept no other receipt than that\nof Mr. Innes.\u201d\n\u201cVery good, sir.**\nHarley took his hat and cane, and\nBenson opened the front door.\n\"Good day, sir,\" said the butler.\n\u201cGood day, Benson,\u201d called Harley,\nharrying out to the waiting cab.\n\"Number 236 South Lambeth Road.\u201d\nI he directed the man.\nOff moved the taxi, and Harley\nlay back upon the cushions heaving\na long sigh. The Irksome period of\nInaction was ended.\nFor the moment he must focus\nupon establishing, beyond query or\ndoubt, the fact that 81r Charles Ab\ningdon bad not died from natural\ncauses.\nTurning his head, he glanced back\n\u2022t the traffic In the street behind\nhim.\nHis cab waa Just on the point of\nturning onvto the slope of Vauxhall\n'\"Bridge. And fifty yards behind,\nj-\nspeeding along the Embankment,\nwaa a small French car The fea\ntures of the driver he had no time\nto observe. But, peering eagerly\nthrough the window, showed the\ndark face of the passenger.\nIf the following car had turned\non to the bridge, Harley might have\nentertained a certain doubt. But,\nmentally putting himself in the pur\nsuer\u2019s place! he imagined himself de\ntected and' knew at once exactly\nwhat he should do. Since this hy\npothetical course was actually pur\nsued by the other, Harley\u2019s belief\nwas confirmed.\nCraning his neck, he saw the little\nFrench car turn abruptly and pro\nceed in the direction of Victoria Sta\ntion. Instantly he acted.\nLeaning out of the window he\nthrust a ten-shilling note into the\ncabman\u2019s hand. \u201cSlow down, but\ndon\u2019t pull up,* 'he directed. \u201cI am\ngoing to jump out Just as you pass\nthat lorry ahead. Ten yards further\non stop. Get down and crank your\nengine, and then proceed slowly\nover the bridge. I shall not want\nyou again.\u201d\nAs a result. Immediately he was\nafforded the necessary cover, Harley\njumped from the cab. The man\nreached back and closed the door,\nproceeding on his leisurely way. Ex\ncepting the driver of the lorry, no\none witnessed this eccentric per\nformance, and Harley, stepping on\nto the footpath, qiiietiy joined the\nstream of pedestrians and strolled\nslowly along.\nHe presently passed the stationary\ncab without giving any sign of\nrecognition to the dismounted\ndriver. Then, a minute later, the\ncab overtook him and was soon lost\nin the traffic ahead. Even as it dis\nappeared another cab went by\nrapidly.\nLeaning forward in order to peer\nthrough the front window was the\ndark-faced man whom he had de\ntected on the Embankment!\n\u201cQuite correct,\u201d murmured Har\nley, dryly. \"Exactly what I should\nhave done.\u201d\nine spy, Knowing nimseix aiscov\neredhad abandoned his own car\nIn fp,vor of a passing taxicab, and In\nthe latter had taken up the pursuit.\nPalul Harley lighted a cigaret.\nThe contest had developed Into\nopen warfare. Harley\u2019s Accurate\nknowledge of London had enabled\nhim to locate No. 236 South Lam\nbeth Road without recourse to a\nguide.\nHe walked quite openly up the\ndilapidated steps to the door of No.\n236, and was about to seize the dirty\nIron knocker when the door opened\nsuddenly and a girt came out. She\nwas dressed neatly and wore a\npseudo fashionable hat from which\na heavy figured veil depended so as\nalmost to hide her features. She was\ncarrying a bulging cane grip se\ncured by a brown leather strap.\nSeeing Harley on the step, she\npaused for a moment, then, recover\ning herself:\n\u201cEllen!\" she shouted down the dim\npassageway revealed by the opening\nof the door. \u201cSomebody to see you.\u201d\nLeaving the door open, she hurried\npast the visitor with averted face.\nHarley grasped the girl\u2019s arm.\n\u201cOne moment. Miss Jones,\u201d he said,\nquietly, \u201cit is you I am here to\nsee!\"\nHe extended his arm to detain her.\nBut she thrust it aside. \u201cMy boy's\nwaiting round the corner!\u201d she said\nviciously. \u201cJust see what he\u2019ll do\nwhen I tell him!\u201d\n\u201cStep inside,\u201d repeated Harley,\nquietly. \u201cOr accompany me to Ken\nnlngton Lane Polioe Statlon-i-which\never you think would he the more\naxpusing.\u201d\nA tired-looking woman carrying a\nchild appeared from somewhere and\nstared apathetically at Harley.\nAddressing the angry girl: \u201cAn\nother o' your flames, Polly T\u201d she In\nquired In a dul voicle. \u201cHas be made\nyou change your mind already?\u201d\nThe girl addressed as \"Polly*\ndropped her grip on the floor and,\nbanging open a door, entered a\nshabby little sitting room, followed\nby Harley.\n\u201cExcuse me, madam, for lntrud\ning,\u201d said Harley to the woman with\nI the baby, \u201cbut Polly has some ln\nformation of use to the police. Oh,\ndon\u2019t be alarmed. She has oom\nmltted no crime. I shall only detain\ni her for a few minutes.\u201d\nThe official manner had Its effect\nMiss Jones looked sharply across\nat the speaker. \u201cI haven\u2019t done\nanything,\u201d she said, sullenly.\nPaul Harley advanced and stood]\nACTIVITIES AMONG THE FARMERS\nCAPPER DECLARES\nFARMERS GAINING\nBDT VERY SLOWLY\nIndications, Point to Substan\ntial Increase in New Year\nSenator Says.\nBY KENNETH CLARK.\nInternational News Service Start\nCorrespondent.\nWASHINGTON, Dec 21.\u2014Ameri\ncan agriculture la slowly climbing\nout of the slump and aU Indications\npoint to a substantial Improvement\nIn the Industry during the new year,\nSen. Arthur Capper, Republican, of\nKansas, declared today In an inter\nview with International News\nService.\nCapper, leader of the farm bloc in\ncongress, is recognized as one of\nAmerica\u2019s most able authorities on\nagriculture.\n\u201cAll indications point to a gradual\nimprovement in the farm economic\nposition during the new year,\u201d Cap\nper said.\n\u201cThe wheat farmer, of course, Is\nnot yet out of the ditch. For three\nyears he has produced wheat at a\nloss, but another year should shoW\nan improvement. The wheat farmer\nis curtailing his acreage; cutting\nhis production to meet more nearly\nthe requirements of the home mar\nket and avoiding surplus production\nwhich is always dlsasterous to him.\nFigures and estimates now available\nIndicate a reduction of wheat acre\nage of about 15 percent.\nuetter Dusmess memoas, coopera\ntion In the marketing of products,\nand some decrease in the spread be\ntween the cost of things he sells\nwill contribute to the Improvement\nIn the farmers\u2019 economlo position.\nHe still has a long way to go before\nhis prosperity Is completely restored.\nHe still Is at the bottom of the lad\nder In comparison with other In\ndustries. He must have sympathetic\nconsideration in any scheme looking\ntowfrd the assurance of Rational\nprosperity during the new year.\nNeed Freight Rate Relief.\n\"His most pressing need Is relief\nfrom excessive transporatlon cost. I\nhope to see substantial redaction in\nfreight rates at an early date.\n'\u2018\u25a0\\yith ampler credit facilities, bet\nter marketing methods and reduc\ntion of acreage, more nearly t* bring\ncrop yields within the requirements\nof the home market demand, the new\nyear should see a marked improve\nment, particular in regard to the\nwheat grower who last year did not\nshare in the upturn in favor of agri\nculture as a whole.\n\u201cAmong the legislative Influences\nthat should have a favorable effect\nin the agriculture industry during\nthe year, reduction of war taxes Is\noutstanding. This should ease the\nburden that productive enterprises\nand business is now foi-ced to carry\nIt is absurdly unfair that earned In\ncome should be penalized and' un\nearned income eased of its share of\nthe costs of government and the li\nquidation of war obligations. Aboli\ntion of the tax exempt privilege\nwould go far toward a more equit\nable distribution of the tax load.\nWhatever tag legislation is written\nshould be written on the basis of\nsucly distribution, share and share\nalike according to ability to pay.\nReturn of Prosperity.\n\"Next in importance, perhaps, to\nthe welfare of business is the read\njustment of freight, rates. Discrim\nnatory and consifacatory freights ar\na major factor in the delay of the\nfarmers\u2019 economic recovery. In the\nsolution of this problem, the farmer\nis entitled to the sympathetic atten\ntion and cooperation of all business\nmen, for the fagmer is not only a\nproducer; he is normally a customer.\n\"As his return to prosperity is\npostponed his disadvantage affects\nthe entire business community,\" Cap\nper said.\n(Copyright 1928, by International\nNews Service.)\nAUTHORIZE PURCHASE\nBy International News Service:\nWASHINGTON. Dec. 21\u2014The in\nterstate commerce commission today\nauthorized the Chicago, Rock Island\nand Pacific railroad to acquire by\npurchase approximately 15 miles of\nrailroad extending from Chattanooga\nto Grandfleld, Okla. The line in\nquestion is owned by the Rock Is\nland and Oklahoma railroad, and\nthe entire capital stock of the road\nis held by the Rock Island system.\nCHEAP'\nAutographs of former Presidents\nhave sold for *360,000. Mr. Cool\nidge\u2019s would bring far more than\nthat if he would affix it to bills that\ncertain people would like to have\nput into effect.\nover her. \u201cWhat about the trick\nwith the serviettes at Sir Charles\nAbingdon\u2019s?\u201d he asked, speaking the\nwords in slow and deliberate fash\nion.\n\u201cDon\u2019t arrest me,\u201d she said. \u201cTO\ntell you.\"\n\u201cGood. In the first place, then,\nwhere were you going when I came\nhere?\"\n\u201cTo meet my boy at VauxhaU Sta\ntion.\"\n\u201cHe has done murder. What is\nhis name?\"\n\"My God!\u201d whispered the girl, and\nher face blanched swiftly. \u201cMur\nder! I\u2014I can\u2019t tell you his name\u2014\u201d\n\u201cToo mean you wont?\u201d\nShe did not answer.\n\"He is a very dark^man,\u201d contin\nued Harley, \u201cwith black eyes. He is\na Hindu.\u201d\n\"Yea\u2014yes? He ft a foreigner.\"\n\"Where was he going to take\nyou\n\u201cI don\u2019t know. He said he could\nput me in a good Job out of London.\nWe had only ten minutes to catch\nthe train. He\u2019s gone to get the!\ntickets.\u201d\n\u201cWhat did you do to the serviettes\non the night Sir Charles died?\u201d\n\u201cSidney\u2014\"\n\u201cOh, he called himself Sidney, did\nbe? It isn^ his name. But go on.\u201d\n\u201cHe asked me to get one of the\nserviettes, with the ring, and to lend\nIt to him.\u201d\n\u201cYou did this?\"\n\u201cYea. But tie brought it back.\"\n\"When?\"\n\"The afternoon\u2014\"\n\u201cBefore Sir Charles* death? Yes.\nGo on. What did he Mil you to do\nwith this serviette?\"\nContinued in Oar Heat Issue\nShe\u2019s Some Cow, Folks!\nForty-eight quarts of milk a day! No, It Isn\u2019t the driver's order for a\nrestaurant. It's the average of aristocratic Carnation Segis Pieterje Pros\npect. She\u2019s heralded as the world\u2019s champion for all breeds and ages. She\ntotaled 35,550.4 pounds this year. Her heat day\u2019s work was 63 quarts.\nCarnation, now 10 years old, is owned by E. A. Stuart of Carnation, Wash.\nShe Is the mother of three sons and a daughter, all blue ribbon winners\nat stock shows.\nWinter Weed Chats\nGetting Rid of Canada Thistle\nBy AliBEBT A. HANSEN.\nPurdue University Department of Agricultural Extension.\nCanada thistle is spreading alarm\ningly throughout the northern half\nof Indiana and odd patches may be\nfound along the Ohio river. In\nNorthern Indiana the plant spreads\nlargely by means of wind-scattered\nseeds, although this is contrary to,\nthe opinion of many farmers.\nThe Canada thistle law is still in\neffect in Indiana. The township\ntrustee can compel you to cut all\nthistles on your land that grow to a\nheight of six inches, or else pay\nboth a fine and the cost of having\nthem cut.\nThe eradication of small patches of\nthe prickly pest is still one of the\n'biggest problems. Many farmers\nhave been sffccessful in doing this\nby cutting the sprouts once a week\nfrom spring until faJl, hut it must\nbe remembered that a,single neglect\ned cutting may spoil the whole job.\nCutting the shoots robs the plant of\nits green tissue and since green tissue\nis necessary to manufacture food, the\nroots will starve to death in a few\nweeks if no green growth is allowed\nto develop.\nAnother and simpler method is to\nallow the thistle to 'blossom (but not\nto develop seeds, which happens\nwhen the__down forms) and cut them\nclose to \"the ground while in full\nflower. Then sprinkle dry salt at the\nrate of one pound per square foot\non the ground where the plants have\njust been cut and \u201cdestroy all the\nshoots for the remainder of the sea\nson before they attain a height of\ntwo Inches.\nWhere just a few shoots occur, cut\nwhen In full flower and squirt crude\ncarbolic acid into the newly cut\nstems with an ordinary spring-bot\ntom oil can, and treat any young\nshoots that may appear later, with a\nsecond dose of crude carbolic.\nA simple and comparatively easy\nmethod of destroying large areas of\nthistles is to grow Grimm alfalfa, a\nmethod that Is strongly recommend\ned. Where good stands of alfalfa can\nnot be obtained, a special system of\ncultivation may be used the details\nof which can be gotten by addressing\nthe Purdue university agricultural\n[extension department, Lafayette, Ind.\nOFFICERS ELECTED\nBY FARM BUREAU\n\nDelbert Shimp to Guide Des\ntimes of Clay-Harris Or\nganization in 1924.\nAbout 40 Farm Bureau men and\nwomen connected with the Clay\nHarris township Farm Bureaus met\nfor their annual meeting- at the home\nof Delbert Shimp, on the Edwards\nburg road in Harris township,\nThursday night. It was decided to\norganize the two townships in a\njoint unit for 1924, holding their\nmeetings together and alternating\neach month between the two town\nships. The following officers were\nelected. President, Delbert Shimp,\nHarris township; vice president, H,\nJ. Longley, Clay township; secretary,\nLeo VanHeee, Clay township./ A\ntreasurer was electea for each town\nship, F. E. Lowery for Harris and\nT. If. Longley for Clay township.\nThe monthly meetings are to be\nheld on the third Wednesday of each\nmonth, the January meeting coming\non Jan. 16 at the Stover school house.\nThe entertainment for the evening\nwas given by the O. W. Schaffner\nCo., who gave a Radio demonstration\n4n charge of L. C. Collars, who is\nin' charge of the Radio Laboratory\nin the Dean building.\nThe two township units have a to\ntal membership of 44 and have ap\npointed a special program commit\ntee to arrange for Farm Bureau ac\ntivities during the winter. C. F.\nKownover was appointed purchasing\nagent for the Clay-Harris Farm\nBureau.\nJust FolKsK\nI I *BBB5SB\u00bb\nTHE BEST\n\"If I were young again,\u201d said he,\n\u201cWhatever I\u2019d eet out to be\u2014\nTrade or profession-\u2014I\u2019d not rest\n\u2022Till I was rated vith the best.\n'\"Were I an office boy once more,\nOr running errands for a store,\nI\u2019d make the man who hired me see\nHow good a boy he had in me.\n\u201cThen If I rose to be clerk,\nI\u2019d never slight the job,\u2019 or shirk;\nI\u2019d be no hilf-way clerk, but one\nThat people could depend upon.\n\"I\u2019ve often wished that I had tried\nWhen I was young, to take more\npride\nIn what I had to do, and be\nOf greater credit unto me.\n\"I could have made myself. I\u2019m sure,\nA reputation to endure;\nI thought it smart when sawing\nwood\nTo cut as little as I could.\n\u2022Too late. I see It all today.\nBut many tread' the self-same way;\nIndifferent to the task or test.\nThey seldom try to do their best\n\u201cOh, boy of mine, whate\u2019er your\nplace.\nWhatever duty you shall face,\nLet no man cay, whate\u2019er you do.\nThat he\u2019s hired better boys than\nyou.\u201d\n(Copyright, IMS, by Fxlgar A.\nGuest.)\nConfectionery, Johnson's, Whit*\nman's\u2014Bastlans. \u2014advt. S5S-T. F.\ni\nV\nFARM ORGANIZATIONS\nSTUDIED AT PURDUE\nA complete and careful study of\nall the more Important farmer or\nganizations which have existed in\nthe United States up to the present\ntime is being made by a class en\nrolled in a farm management course\nat Purdue university this year.\nThis course has been given only a\nshort time but it bids fair to be a\nuseful and important addition to the'\ncurriculum. The present national in\nterest in the American Farm Bureau\nfederation has stimulated much\nthought along farm organization\nlines. It is the object of this course\nto be able to interpret^the present\nmovement intelligently by compar\ning it to others which have existed\nin the past. Using the history of\nformer organizations, the student is\nable to arrive at some definite con\nclusions which may be applied to\npresent day movements.\nAs the course is being given at\npresent it consists of analyzing each\norganization from four different\nviewpoints: (X) Reasons for estab\nlishment; (2) form of organization,\n(3) program advocated and (4) ac\ncomplishments. Regarding the rea\nsons for establishment, the study\nshows that almost invariably the or\nganizations started during periods Of\ndepression when farmers are seem\ningly easily convinced that their dis\ntress is the fruits of their own in\ndividualism and that economic sal\nvation. lies in group action.\nThere have been all forms of or\nganizations ranging from the Orange\na secret fraternal order, closely or\nganized, to the Farmer\u2019s National\ncongress which is a mere resolution\norganization. The programs, as the\nstudy reveals, show a striking simil\narity. Organizations back in the\nsixties had such features as: cheaper\niransporcauon, control or prices, re\nadjustment of the money and credit\nsystem, elimination of middlemen,\nand many others which are in the\nprograms of present day organiza\ntions.\nThe study shows that much good\nhas undoubtedly been accomplished\nby these organizations. Improve\nment of agricultural education, the\nestablishment of experiment station,\nI rural free delivery and many other\nmatters were championed by them\nlong before such measures were a\npart of the educational and govern\nmental systems.\nCoroner9s Jury Weighs\nDwd Death Mystery\nBy United Pres*:\nLINCOLN, Neb., Dec. 21.\u2014A cor\noner's jury Tyas to decide who killed\nMr. and Mrs. L. R. Whitney, found\nshot to death In the room back of\nI their grocery store here yesterday\nPolice have a series of facts\nwhich they believe proves Whitney\nin a quarrel shot and killed his wife\nand then placed the revolver in his\nmouth and killed himself.\nThe half-clothed bodies were lying\nside by side when police, summoned\nby customers unable to get Into the\nstore, broke through the barred\nj doors.\nA murder theory was soon aban\ndoned after police found the only\nmeans of entrance Into the room\nbarred and locked from the Inside.\nBoth were shot through the hdad.\nDANGEROUS DATS\nFor a year at least we have seen\nthe last of the season when the fa\nther of the family puts a mortgage\non the house and buys four seats\nfor a football game with the pro\nceeds.\nBY J. R BABCOCK;\nJjBOjiinq <Aoh JonqQ (Authority*and,]\nauthor of \u2018Babcock'? xeaLSook ot<Rnlet\\ J\nNo. 10\u2014Scoring and Paying\nScores are computed and differ\nences settled after each hand.\nWhen a vplayer declares Mah\nJongg, he exposes the hitherto con\ncealed portion of his hand, being\ncareful not to confuse It with his al\nready exposed tiles. His score for\nboth concealed and exposed combl\nr\ntile obtained wu the 2 Character,\nthe 8 Character, the 6 Character,\nthe 2 Bamboo, the 8 Bamboo, or the\n7 Bamboo,\nIjoweet Score\nTwenty-two ie the lowest scoring\ncombination for a winning hand. In\nthe above hand, had the three o( a\nkind In Dots been replaced by an\n-1\nHuatrition. A\nt-| n JL-- J VT 711,7. 0\u2014\u25a0 n n i\nIiluatution B\nfttufitntioa C\n\u20141T\nnations Is then totaled, including all\ndoubles.\nIf th?winning player ie other than\nEast, he collects an amount in coun\nters from two of the players equal\nto his points, and twice this amount\nfrom East.\nIf the winner is East, he collects\ndouble from each of the other three\nplayers.\nPaying Up\nWhen the winner has been paid,\nthe other three players total their\nscores and each pays or collects from\nthe other two (except in case of a\ntie) on the basis of the dilerence in\ntheir scores. Thus, A scores 20, B\n25 and C 35. A pays B 6 and C 15.\nB pays C 36. In case either A, B\nor C had been East, he would have\npaid or collected just double these\namounts, as East always pays or col\nlects double.\nIn scoring, tiles can be used in one\ncombination only, and the exposed\nand concealed hands cannot be mix\ned. All tiles in the exposed hand\nmust be left in the combinations In\nwhich they were declared.\nThe following model hands will\nhelp you fix in your hand methods\nof scoring.\nIf on If in\nTable Hand\nFor three 3a....- 2 4\nFor Mah Jongg\n(or winning). 20 20\n22 24\nTo this total of 22 (or 24) would\nbe added:\nIf winning tile was drawn from\nwall, 2 points;\nIf winning piece was only possible\npiece to complete hand, 2 points.\nIn this hand, you would score for\nonly possible place to win If the last\nSIMPLE THINGS YOU\nMAY DO\nNowadays\u2019 when women have\nbecome more capable and less orna\nmental, they are likely to pay the\nprice of t^eir increased freedom by\nlosing: some of the clinging-vine\nbeauty of other days, that is,, unless\nthey take extra precautions.\nWe know that fifty years ago the\nmifl-Victorian novelists boasted of\nthe lily-white hands and tapering\nfingers of their' heroines. We also\nknow that modern heroines use\ntheir hands to accomplish so many\nother thing besides sewing fine\nseams, that they must take extra\nprecautions to keep them beautiful.\nFor no matter how proud a woman\nmay be of her work, she never likes\nto have her hands look as If she\nused them very much! So much for\nfeminine' vanity, which after all is\na very charming quality.\nIt is very true that the hands re\nquire special care if they are always\nto appear in the pink of perfection.\nThis is true no matter what the\nwork the hands in question do,' but\nit is especially true if their task is\nhousework.\nIf yop have as your daily task the\nusual jobs that must be done about\nthe house\u2014dishwashing and clean\ning and dusting\u2014there is one thing\nyou must practice always, and this is\nthe wearing of gloves.\nWhen you sweep, pqt on thick\ngloves to protect your hands. It\ndoesn't matter how many sizes too\nbig they are. In fact they should be\nseveral sizes larger than gloves\nyou\u2019d wear on the street, for you\nneed plenty of freedom of move\nments.\nIt\u2019s a very good plan to find son\\e\ndiscarded thick kid gloves of a male\nmember of the family, for they are\nlikely to be soft and heavy. For\ndusting and light housework, light\nother sequence, the above hand\nwould hav scored the consolation\nbonus of 10.\nIf on If In\nTable Hand\nFor three 4s. 2 4\nFor three Dragons...; 4 8\nFor Mah Jongg...... 20 20\n26 64\nDoubling for 3 dragons 52 64\nDoubling for all of one\nsuit (except honors) 104 128\nIf winner were West In above\nhand, two more would be added be\nfore doubling for \u201cpair of own\nwinds.\"\nIf on If In\nTable Hand\nFor three Is.. 4 8\nFor three 6s. 2 4\nFor Mah Jongg. 20 20\n26 32\nDoubling three times for\nall of .one suit.... 208 256\nNext Article: The Seasons\nweight chamois gloves are prefer\nable to kid. And you should never\nfall to wear rubber gloves when\ndoing the dishes, for hot, greasy\nwater is 'devastating to beauty of\nhands.\nWhile this may sound rather\ntroublesome, having three separate\npairs of gloves for different house\nhold activities. It really is little or\nno trouble at all, and it means\neverything to the beauty of your\nhands. Simply keep your, gloves\nhandy, and slip on the pair needed\nfor the activity at hand. Then\nwhen you want to do some delicate\nwork on a fine seam you will have\ndainty, attractive hands of which\nyou can well be proud.\nNow I\u2019m going to tell you an ex\ncellent method of preserving and\nenhancing the beauty of youn hands\nat the same time that you clean\nhouse.\nWhen you are ready to don your\nheavy sweeping gloves or your\nlight-weight dusting gloves, rub a\nlittle grease cream into the palms of\nyour hands, also touching the cuticle\nof each nail lightly with the grease\ncream.\nThen draw your finger-nails down\na cake 'of good soap, as if you were\nscratching it. This will fill your\nnails with the soap, which is cleans\ning and beautifying if it stays in\nlong enough. You can now pull\non your gloves and go merrily about\nyour housework.\nWhen it is finished remove your\nglbves and wash your hands in\nwarm water with good soap. Scrub\nyour nails with a camel's hair nail\nbrush. When the soap that has\nbeen between the tip of your finger\nand your nail is removed, you\u2019ll find\nyour nail whiter than It was before.\nOatmeal, made into a paste by\nadding water, is an excellent\ncleaner. If your hands are very\ndry and inclined to chapping, clean\nthem with a grease cream before\nyou use the oatmeal cleanser.\nIf you follow these instructions\nfaithfully you can have beautiful,\ndainty hands, though you do your\nown housework.\nNOTICE.\nWe are making cider today and\ntomorrow. Get it fresh from press\nfor your Christmas dihner. 25c per\ngallon. I. R. Butzbach, 106 N. St.\nJoseph st.\n\u2014Adv. p. m. 335-357 p. m.\nWhere is your auto certificate of\nownership? Get a safety deposit\nbox and make sure. Open evenings.\nMourer Ins. Security Co.,' Oliver\nHotel Bldg.\n\u2014Adv. p. m. 352-357 p. m.\nEUROPE HOARDS\nYANKEE DOLLARS\nCounterfeiters Reap Rich Ha\u00bb\u00bb\nvest in Old World by\n\u201cMaking\u201d U. S. Money.\nBr ROBERT S. THORNBURGH,\nI. X. S. Staff Correspondent,\nWASHINGTON. Deo. 21.\u2014A inert*\ncan currency held, or In circulation\nabroad, amounts to from half a bil\nlion to three-quarters of a billion\ndollars, it became known today In\nconnection with a federal Investi\ngation of the situation.\nA considerable percentage of this\nenormous fund Is \"salted away\" In\nsafety deposit vaults, and other hid\ning places of money, awaiting a fa\nvorable time for investment in for\neign currency or American securl-\nties.\nAn intensive study to determine\nthe exact amount of the American\nmoney abroad the amount exported\nannually in \"emigrant remittances,\u201d\nand spent overseas by tourists, has\nbeen launched by the department\nof commerce, bureaus of the treas\nury and other financial and statisti\ncal departments.\nIn this probe many lnterestlnff\nfacts have developed.\nNoteworthy-araong them is a new\n\"business\"\u2014the counterfeiting of\nAmerican money in foreign coun\ntries. Government officials have been\nasked by the Austrian bankers' asso\nelation for all information in dealing\nwith counterfeiters, the making of\nspurious American money being par\nticularly prevalent in that nation.\nNo Action Planned.\nNo action is contemplated by this\ngovernment against counterfeiting\nabroad, but it was understood that\nseveral foreign countries, whose cur\nrency is almost worthless are talc\ning steps to prosecute counterfeiter*\nfob fraud and obtaining money un\nder false pretenses, the spurious\nspecie being disposed of there as\nthe genuine American article.\nBecause the American dlolar has\nbecome a currency standard in\nmany European countries, counter\nfeiters of both eilver and paper mon\ney are getting rich, according to Of\nficial information.\nThe Investigation developed that\na considerable quantity of worthless\nmoney of the American confederacy,\nused during the Civil war, wgs taken\nabroad and disposed of as currency\nof the United States.\nEmigrant remittances which, In\n1922, amounted to about $400,000,\n000, according to official' estimates\nwill not exceed that amount in 192$.\nMost of the remittances this year\nhave been made in $5, $10 and $20\nbills.\nAmerican tourist expenditures in\n1923 were considerably below tha\napproximate $350,fl00,000 o\u00a30 1922,\npreliminary estimates show. Fewer\npersons went abroad during the past\nsummer and autumn. On the other\nhand moreu foreigners visited this\ncountry and are believed to have\nspent about 1100,000,000.\nThe American dollar has become\nalmost a fetish In continental Eur\nope.\n\u201cAll classes have become Imbued\nwith a single n^d undivided faith In\nAmerican dollars,\" said a statement\nfrom United States Consul Walter\nS. Relneck, of Budapest.\n\u201cWaiters, porters, clerks, huslneM\nand professional men, and farmers\nall have bought dollars and hoarded\nthem. These dollars are deposited\nin safety deposit vaults, hidden away\nIn homes or locked In safes.\"\nBritish Threaten Break\nWith Afghanistan\nBy International NewB Service:\nLONDON, Dec. 21.\u2014Great Britlan\nhas threatened to break, off diplo\nmatic relations with Afghanistan un\nless satisfaction Is given for murders\ncommitted along the Afghan-Ifrdian\nfrontier, the Daily Express reported\ntoday.\nAccording to this newspaper*\nGreat Britlan threatened to close\nKhyber Pass, which would seriously\nhamper Afghan trade.\nGet your garments and hats clean\ned now. Do not wait for the last\nday. Ladies suits pressed or men\u2019s\nsuits pressed and cleaned, $1.50.\nExtra for delivery. Any kind of hat\ncleaned, 60c. t\nAETNA CLEANER HATTERS,\nLincoln 2376 916 E. Sample at*\n\u2014advt. 346lf\nFannie May Candy for Christmas\nat the Blue Gate Shop. Oliver HotaL\n\u2014Adv.354-357.\n1\nEchakpii\nfor Constipation\nm the Gulf Coast\non your trip\nPASS\nN CHRISTIAN\nORLCANS^54v>\n_.\nto FLORIDA\nSi FROM\nBILOXI v^\\ THE\n1 _Ssj NDDTU\nLittle or No\nExtra Expense\n